Enforces a vocabulary of retired identifiers — terms that ADRs have formally deprecated — rejecting them anywhere outside history/rationale docs and the audit trail. The script scans git-tracked source files (via `git ls-files`, matching other scripts/ checks) and fails if a banned term appears in live code, help text, comments, README, prompts, or CLAUDE.md; `.context/` is excluded since it regenerates on reseed.

The `BANNED` array at the top enumerates retired terms — add here when an ADR retires an identifier. The `is_allowed()` function whitelists the rationale ledger (`docs/DECISIONS.md`), retired-design history (`docs/retired/**`), audit docs (`docs/AUDIT.md`, `docs/OPUS_CONTEXT_FRESHNESS_PROMPT.md`), and this script itself.

The grep uses `-H` (force filename prefix) with `/dev/null` appended to guarantee `path:line:content` output format even on single files; ctx-verify's `split_loc` parser expects this exact form and reads only up to the line number to extract location, so diagnostic text appended after the line is free-form guidance. Exit code 1 if any match is found.